<h2 id="FleetManagement">Fleet Management</h2>
<h3>Overview</h3>
<p>
    Each player has two sets of fleet lists. One of these is the Home Fleet and the other is the Assault Fleet.
    These lists contain the units from which all other army lists are drawn.
    The Home Fleet is used for defensive army lists and the Assault fleet is used for offensive army lists.
    During a turn a unit on the army list may normally only be used once.
    This means that it may be possible that no valid army list can be made!
    Players are expected to create valid army lists whenever possible, and in cases where this is not possible they should make it as close to valid as they possibly can.
    If an invalid list is to be used, the opposing player should be informed and should approve the list to ensure that this approach is not abused (e.g., no lists where 80% of the list consists of dreadnoughts).
    When a defending player does not have sufficient points available to create a defensive list, he or she should draw units from the Assault fleet to create a valid army list.
    If all these steps have been taken and the defending player still does not have sufficient units available to defend, the defending player probably isn't long for this campaign anyway.
</p>
<h3>Repairs</h3>
<p>
    At the end of a battle ships may lie broken and battered. Mighty dreadnoughts are reduced to scrap metal. All damage to units and fortifications is done on a permanent basis. SAWs are replenished for free.
</p>
<p>
    At the beginning of a turn each ship automatically repairs 2 hull points (3 with a drydock). This means that most small vessels may be repaired free of charge. For each additional hull point to be repaired, 1 RP per 2 repaired HP (rounded up) must be spend. Remember that you can chose to not fully repair a unit, however if you use this unit in battle it will be damaged from the start.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Example:</strong> A 3-strong squadron of Riever cruisers engages in an assault. At the end of the assault one of the Rievers is destroyed, one has taken three damage and one has taken one damage. At the beginning of the repair step 1 RP must be paid to recover the destroyed Riever. It recovers two hull points automatically, leaving two hull points to be repaired. The other Rievers also regenerate two hull points. One Riever (with two hull points of damage) is repaired to full, the other one (with three hull points of damage) has one point of damage left to repair. This costs one additional RP.
</p>
<p>
    In total this cruiser squadron has taken 4 + 3 + 2 = 9 hull points of damage. Of those, 2 + 2 + 2 = 6 hull points were repaired automatically. 3 hull points remaining cost 3 RP to repair and 1 additional RP is paid for the destroyed Riever, thus the player has to pay 4 RP to restore the Riever squad to full working order.
</p>
<p>
    Also note that the Home Fleet is allowed repairs between battles if you are attacked multiple times in one turn. This can cause you to have negative RP. This extra repair chance only applies to damage taken in the current turn and you pay 1 RP per 1 HP when doing this, reflecting crews working over time to get the ship fixed. This means that if I choose not to fully repair a unit from my home fleet its maximum HP for that turn is reduced. Also note that the "free" 2 HP repair only applies at the start of the next turn. 
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Example:</strong> A Liberty and Savannah from the Home Fleet are destroyed in a battle. The player chooses to fully repair the Liberty but does not repair the Savannah. This means that the maximum HP of the Savannah is 2 for the whole turn. This player is then attacked 2 times. In the first battle the Liberty takes 5 damage, the player also wants to use the Liberty for the second battle and repairs it to full, paying 5 RP. The Liberty then takes 6 damage. At the end of the turn the Liberty has 3 HP remaining. 
</p>
<p>
    If a fortification is destroyed, it may not be repaired. Instead the owning player must pay 50% of the territory upgrade to rebuild the upgrade (mines excluded). If the fortification is merely damaged, RP must be spend to repair it as normal.
</p>
<h3>Expanding the fleet lists</h3>
<p>
    As the campaign progresses, players may find that they are in need of more units for their fleets. New units may be bought during the fleet management phase. Each new <strong>squadron</strong> costs 1 RP + 1 RP per hull point. For example, a Requin corvette squadron has 5 units with 2 hullpoints each. To build a full squadron this would cost 5 * 2 + 1 = 11 RP. When bought the unit is added to a fleet and may be used from the next turn onwards.
</p>
<h3>Adding Allied units</h3>
<p>
    A player may also wish to add allied units to his force. These units go into a seperate list, the Ally list. The units in this can be used for the Home and Assault fleet, however not both at the same time. The units are build and repaired the same as with normal units. Also the normal ally rules from the Dystopian Wars rulebook apply when using allies in a battle. 
</p>
