<h2 id="Alliances">Alliances</h2>
<h3>Overview</h3>
<p>
    Players may have one of three types of relationship with other players. Either they are at war, they have a cease-fire or they have an alliance.
</p>
<p>
    Players start out without any allegiance whatsoever. Even if two players use the same faction, they do not start with an alliance or even cease-fire. If two players wish to broker a cease-fire agreement or alliance both have to declare this during Turn Phase #5: Resolve map updates. This means that they'll be able to coordinate attacks in their next turn, but other players will have the opportunity to strike as well. To commit to an alliance, both players must be in a cease-fire agreement beforehand for a full turn.
</p>
<h4>At War</h4>
<p>
    This is the default relationship between two players. Both players can freely attack each other.
</p>
<h4>Cease-Fire Agreement</h4>
<p>
    When a cease-fire agreement is in place, both players have agreed not to attack each other. They may not pass through each others territories nor benefit from territory upgrades the other player controls. Example: if an allied player controls a Radar Array next to an area where you are fighting, you do not gain the reroll for strategic advantage.
</p>
<p>
    Cease-fire agreements may be broken unilaterally at any point in the game. This means that a player can blindside a player he or she has a cease-fire agreement with. If used in a hostile manner though (example: sneak attack), the offending player may not agree to cease-fire agreements for three turns.
</p>
<h4>Alliance</h4>
<p>
    When an alliance is in place, both players have agreed to work in concert to achieve their goals. They may benefit from fortification upgrades their allies confer. Example: if you fight in an area adjacent to an allies' Airfield you gain 10 SAWs. (Keep in mind they are your allies factions SAWs and thus may not benefit from your carrier actions unless both players are the same faction!)
</p>
<p>
    Upon mutual agreement, an allied player may fight any battle in lieu of his ally, with the exception of conquest. The ally may defend for his or her ally during a conquest battle, but may not conquer territory for his or her ally. The non-fighting player provides the RP for the battle. If a Prussian player were to substitute for a French battle, the French player would pay the RP and the Prussians would resolve the conflict. Note that the French player does not pay for the repairs of the Prussian fleet!
</p>
<p>
    An allied player may request RP from the other player to fund repairs, battles or advantages. An allied player may not request RP to aid in upgrading his or her territories.
</p>
<h3>Allied Detachments</h3>
<p>
    Players may only freely include allied detachments that consist of nations that are not actively participating in the campaign (e.g. the French Republic can take allies from the Ottoman Empire). If a player wishes to include detachments from a nation that is active in this campaign, both players must be part of the same alliance. Furthermore, permission to use the allied detachment must be granted by the allied nation.
</p>
<h3>Mercenaries</h3>
<p>
    Players may include mercenaries in their forces. Mercenaries are not added to the fleets as normal. Instead, they are requisitioned on a per-battle basis, where the hiring player has to pay 1 RP per 2 hull points (rounding up). The player does not pay for repairs on the mercenary ships.
</p>
